# Envoy HCM Filter-Chain — Test Coverage Gap Analysis

**Scope:** `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc`, `source/common/http/filter_manager.cc`,
`source/common/http/header_map_impl.cc`

**Existing test files reviewed:**
- `test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test.cc` / `_test_2.cc` / `_test_3.cc`
- `test/common/http/conn_manager_misc_test.cc`
- `test/common/http/filter_manager_test.cc`
- `test/common/http/header_map_impl_test.cc`
- `test/integration/multiplexed_integration_test.cc` (integration-level only)

---

## Gap 1 — `onConnectionDurationTimeout`: no-codec branch

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **File** | `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc` |
| **Lines** | 772–776 |
| **Risk** | 🔴 HIGH |

### Code

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:769
void ConnectionManagerImpl::onConnectionDurationTimeout() {
  ENVOY_CONN_LOG(debug, "max connection duration reached", read_callbacks_->connection());
  if (codec_) {
    codec_->goAway();
    drain_state_ = DrainState::Closing;
    checkForDeferredClose(false);
  } else {
    // Lines 772-776: timer fires before any HTTP codec is created
    doConnectionClose(Network::ConnectionCloseType::FlushWrite,
                      StreamInfo::CoreResponseFlag::DurationTimeout,
                      "max_duration_timeout_no_codec");
  }
}
```

### Why it is untested

All existing unit tests that exercise `onConnectionDurationTimeout`
(`ConnectionDurationSafeHttp1`, `ConnectionDurationTimeout`, `ConnectionDurationSafeHttp2`)
exercise only the `codec_ != nullptr` path — they all send an initial HTTP request so the codec
is instantiated before the timer fires. No test fires the timer on a raw TCP connection that has
not yet submitted any HTTP bytes.

### Concrete test proposal

```
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, ConnectionDurationTimeoutBeforeCodec) {
  // 1. Configure max_connection_duration = 100ms.
  // 2. Do NOT call fake_input() with HTTP bytes (leave codec_ == nullptr).
  // 3. Advance simulated time by 101ms so the timer fires.
  // 4. EXPECT_CALL(*connection_, close(Network::ConnectionCloseType::FlushWrite)).Times(1);
  // 5. Verify downstream_cx_max_duration_reached counter incremented.
}
```

Add to `test/common/http/conn_manager_misc_test.cc` alongside the
`ConnectionDurationSafeHttp1` family.

### Why it matters

A misbehaving or slow client that holds a TCP connection open (TLS handshake stalls,
no HTTP/1.1 preamble sent) and keeps it open past `max_connection_duration` will trigger this
exact branch. Without a unit test the `doConnectionClose` argument list is refactor-fragile;
the `codec_ == nullptr` guard could be silently broken by renaming the else-branch logic.

---

## Gap 2 — `chargeStats`: InternalRedirect stat suppression

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **File** | `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc` |
| **Lines** | 1079–1083 |
| **Risk** | 🟡 MEDIUM |

### Code

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:1070
void ConnectionManagerImpl::chargeStats(const ResponseHeaderMap& headers) {
  uint64_t response_code = Utility::getResponseStatus(headers);
  // ...
  if (filter_manager_.streamInfo().responseCodeDetails() ==
      StreamInfo::ResponseCodeDetails::get().InternalRedirect) {
    // Lines 1079-1083: skip ALL downstream response-code stats for internal redirects
    return;
  }
  // downstream_rq_completed_, downstream_rq_2xx_, etc. incremented here
  ...
}
```

### Why it is untested

`grep -r "InternalRedirect" test/common/http/` yields no unit test that calls `chargeStats`
with `responseCodeDetails() == "InternalRedirect"`. Existing tests for `chargeStats` all
supply a normal `200 OK` response; none verifies that `downstream_rq_completed` and the
`downstream_rq_2xx` bucket are **not** incremented when the detail is `InternalRedirect`.

### Concrete test proposal

```
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, InternalRedirectSuppressesStats) {
  // 1. Set up a request/response cycle that ends with responseCodeDetails
  //    == StreamInfo::ResponseCodeDetails::get().InternalRedirect.
  // 2. Call chargeStats() (triggered via doEndStream or sendLocalReply).
  // 3. EXPECT that stats_.named_.downstream_rq_completed_.value() == 0
  //    and stats_.named_.downstream_rq_2xx_.value() == 0.
  // 4. Contrast with a non-redirect path that DOES increment those counters.
}
```

Add to `test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test.cc`.

### Why it matters

`chargeStats` is the sole accounting point for downstream request counters used by
Prometheus metrics and rate-limiting. An accidental removal of the `InternalRedirect`
guard would double-count internally-redirected requests, inflating SLO/error-budget metrics.
Since `return` is the only action and there is no assertion anywhere, a silent regression
here would be invisible without this test.

---

## Gap 3 — `maybeDrainDueToPrematureResets`: early-drain sub-path

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **File** | `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc` |
| **Lines** | 727–733 |
| **Risk** | 🔴 HIGH |

### Code

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:702
void ConnectionManagerImpl::maybeDrainDueToPrematureResets() {
  if (drained_due_to_premature_resets_) {   // lines 716-718: re-entry guard
    return;
  }
  const uint64_t limit = runtime_.snapshot().getInteger(
      "http.max_requests_per_io_cycle", UINT64_MAX);

  // Lines 727-733: early-drain BEFORE the connection has seen enough resets
  // to trip the absolute threshold, but the ratio already looks abusive.
  if (closed_non_internally_destroyed_requests_ < limit &&
      number_premature_stream_resets_ * 2 >= limit) {
    drained_due_to_premature_resets_ = true;
    // calls doConnectionClose(...)
    ...
  }
  ...
}
```

### Why it is untested

The only coverage for this function is in
`test/integration/multiplexed_integration_test.cc` (lines 3072–3097 and 1397–1404).
Those end-to-end tests exercise the happy path where reset counts cross the absolute
threshold. No unit test in `test/common/http/` constructs the specific state
`closed_non_internally_destroyed_requests_ < limit` AND
`number_premature_stream_resets_ * 2 >= limit` in isolation.

### Concrete test proposal

```
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, PrematureResetEarlyDrain) {
  // 1. Set runtime key http.max_requests_per_io_cycle = 10.
  // 2. Inject 4 completed non-internal streams (closed_non_internally_ = 4).
  // 3. Inject 5 premature resets (number_premature_stream_resets_ = 5).
  //    → 4 < 10  AND  5*2=10 >= 10 → should drain.
  // 4. EXPECT_CALL(*codec_, shutdownNotice()).Times(1)  (or equivalent drain action).
  // 5. Verify drained_due_to_premature_resets_ flag is set to prevent re-entry.
}
```

Add to `test/common/http/conn_manager_misc_test.cc`.

### Why it matters

This code implements a DoS mitigation: a client sending a flood of streams that it
immediately resets can exhaust server resources. The early-drain sub-path is the
first trip-wire. Without a unit test, off-by-one errors in the `* 2 >= limit`
arithmetic are undetectable via the integration tests alone, and regressions would
silently degrade the anti-DoS property.

---

## Gap 4 — `refreshDurationTimeout`: gRPC offset ≥ remaining timeout clamping

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **File** | `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc` |
| **Lines** | 1735–1737 |
| **Risk** | 🟡 MEDIUM |

### Code

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:1731
if (timeout != std::chrono::milliseconds(0) && route->grpcTimeoutHeaderOffset()) {
  const auto offset = route->grpcTimeoutHeaderOffset().value();
  if (offset < timeout) {
    timeout -= offset;
  } else {
    // Lines 1735-1737: offset >= timeout → clamp to 0
    timeout = std::chrono::milliseconds(0);
  }
}
```

### Why it is untested

Existing tests for `GrpcTimeout` in `conn_manager_impl_test.cc` mock
`grpcTimeoutHeaderOffset()` and verify that `toGrpcTimeout` is called with a
correct value when `offset < timeout`. No test constructs the case
`offset >= timeout` that exercises the `else` branch at line 1736.
The timer is subsequently enabled with `timeout = 0ms`, which means the
stream would be terminated immediately — a meaningfully different outcome.

### Concrete test proposal

```
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, GrpcOffsetClampsToZero) {
  // 1. Set grpc-timeout header: "500m" (500ms).
  // 2. Configure route grpcTimeoutHeaderOffset = 600ms (> 500ms).
  // 3. Advance simulated clock by 0ms (stream just started).
  // 4. Call refreshDurationTimeout().
  // 5. EXPECT max_stream_duration_timer_->enableTimer(0ms) is called,
  //    meaning the stream-duration timer fires immediately.
  // 6. Verify the stream is terminated via onStreamMaxDurationReached().
}
```

Add to `test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test.cc`.

### Why it matters

If an operator misconfigures `grpcTimeoutHeaderOffset` larger than the typical
gRPC timeout arriving in headers, **every** gRPC stream is silently clamped to
0ms and terminated instantly. Without this test the `else` branch has never
fired under test, so the timer callback wiring could break in refactors.

---

## Gap 5 — `onDeferredRequestProcessing`: deferred-trailers branch

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **File** | `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc` |
| **Lines** | 2558–2561 |
| **Risk** | 🟡 MEDIUM |

### Code

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:2533
bool ConnectionManagerImpl::ActiveStream::onDeferredRequestProcessing() {
  ...
  // Headers (and optionally data) are dispatched above.
  // Lines 2558-2561: dispatch deferred request trailers
  if (deferred_request_trailers_ != nullptr) {
    request_trailers_ = std::move(deferred_request_trailers_);
    filter_manager_.decodeTrailers(*request_trailers_);
  }
  return true;
}
```

### Why it is untested

Existing tests in `conn_manager_impl_test_3.cc` for deferred request processing
(`DeferredRequestProcessing*`) inject headers and body, but none injects
`deferred_request_trailers_`. The `deferred_request_trailers_ != nullptr` branch
at line 2558 is therefore never reached. The move-assignment of `request_trailers_`
and the subsequent `decodeTrailers` call are entirely untested.

### Concrete test proposal

```
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, DeferredRequestProcessingWithTrailers) {
  // 1. Enable request deferral (set max_requests_during_dispatch_ = 1,
  //    ensure deferred_request_processing_callback_ is initialized).
  // 2. Submit a first request that saturates the dispatch budget.
  // 3. Submit a second request with headers + data + trailers;
  //    the whole thing lands in deferred state.
  // 4. Advance the event loop one cycle to trigger onDeferredRequestProcessing().
  // 5. EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filter_, decodeTrailers(_)).Times(1).
  // 6. Verify request_trailers_ is populated on the active stream.
}
```

Add to `test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test_3.cc`.

### Why it matters

Requests with trailers (e.g. gRPC with trailing metadata, chunked HTTP/1.1 with
final chunk trailers) pass through this path under high-load dispatch deferral.
Missing coverage means any future change to the deferred-trailers ownership transfer
(the `std::move`) could silently cause use-after-free or a null pointer dereference
when `decodeTrailers` runs.

---

## Gap 6 — `validateTrailers`: HTTP/2 underscore-in-trailer-name stream-reset path

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **File** | `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc` |
| **Lines** | 1283–1286 |
| **Risk** | 🟡 MEDIUM |

### Code

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:1256
bool ConnectionManagerImpl::ActiveStream::validateTrailers(RequestTrailerMap& trailers) {
  if (!header_validator_) return true;
  auto validation_result = header_validator_->validateRequestTrailers(trailers);
  ...
  // Lines 1283-1286: H/2 special case — underscore in trailer name → stream reset
  if (failure_details == UhvResponseCodeDetail::get().InvalidUnderscore &&
      connection_manager_.codec_->protocol() == Protocol::Http2) {
    filter_manager_.streamInfo().setResponseCodeDetails(failure_details);
    resetStream();    // ← no 400, just a reset
    ...
  }
}
```

### Why it is untested

`validateTrailers` is called from `onRequestTrailers`. Searching
`test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test*.cc` and
`test/extensions/http/header_validators/` for any test that both:
(a) installs a UHV `header_validator_` on an H/2 stream, and
(b) sends request trailers containing an underscore-named trailer field
yields zero results. The H/2-specific `resetStream()` branch
(as opposed to the `sendLocalReply(400, ...)` branch used for H/1)
is exercised only indirectly in codec-level fuzzing, never in a focused unit test.

### Concrete test proposal

```
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, ValidateTrailersH2UnderscoreResets) {
  // 1. Configure H/2 codec (protocol_ = Protocol::Http2).
  // 2. Install a UHV that rejects headers with underscores.
  // 3. Send a request with request trailers containing "x_bad_trailer: value".
  // 4. EXPECT_CALL on stream encoder: resetStream(StreamResetReason::LocalReset, _).
  // 5. EXPECT that sendLocalReply is NOT called (no 400 response on H/2 for this case).
  // 6. Verify DownstreamProtocolError response flag is set.
}
```

Add to `test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test.cc`.

### Why it matters

This is a protocol-specific divergence documented via `TODO(#24466)`.
Without a test, any future harmonization effort (making H/2 send 400 instead of reset)
could inadvertently introduce a breaking change for existing H/2 clients that rely on
the reset behavior.

---

## Gap 7 — `sendLocalReply`: post-response-headers-sent reset branch

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **File** | `source/common/http/filter_manager.cc` |
| **Lines** | 1066–1074 |
| **Risk** | 🔴 HIGH |

### Code

```cpp
// filter_manager.cc:998
void DownstreamFilterManager::sendLocalReply(...) {
  ...
  if (!filter_manager_callbacks_.responseHeaders().has_value() && ...) {
    // normal path — send via filter chain
    ...
  } else if (!state_.non_100_response_headers_encoded_) {
    // bypass filter chain, write directly to codec
    sendDirectLocalReply(...);
  } else {
    // Lines 1066-1074: response headers already committed downstream
    // — only option is a stream reset
    ENVOY_STREAM_LOG(debug, "Resetting stream due to {}. Prior headers already sent", ...);
    // TODO(snowp): This means we increment the tx_reset stat which we weren't doing previously.
    filter_manager_callbacks_.resetStream();   // ← entire else branch untested
  }
}
```

### Why it is untested

`filter_manager_test.cc` contains no test that drives
`state_.non_100_response_headers_encoded_ == true` before calling `sendLocalReply`.
To reach this branch an encoder filter must call `sendLocalReply` after the codec
has already committed a non-informational response header frame downstream.
No existing unit test constructs this ordering.

### Concrete test proposal

```
TEST_F(FilterManagerTest, SendLocalReplyAfterResponseHeadersEncoded) {
  // 1. Add an encoder filter that buffers.
  // 2. Let the filter chain encode 200 OK headers (sets
  //    non_100_response_headers_encoded_ = true).
  // 3. Inside the encoder filter's encodeData callback, call
  //    decoder_callbacks_->sendLocalReply(Code::InternalServerError, ...).
  // 4. EXPECT_CALL(filter_manager_callbacks_, resetStream()).Times(1).
  // 5. Verify no further encode calls are made.
}
```

Add to `test/common/http/filter_manager_test.cc`.

### Why it matters

This branch is the last-resort error handler when a filter detects a fatal error
*after* a 200 response was already partially sent. Without it tested, the `resetStream()`
call could be accidentally removed or moved, resulting in the connection hanging
indefinitely rather than being torn down, which would exhaust file descriptors.

---

## Gap 8 — `prepareLocalReplyViaFilterChain`: second-call idempotency guard

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **File** | `source/common/http/filter_manager.cc` |
| **Lines** | 1088–1090 |
| **Risk** | 🟡 MEDIUM |

### Code

```cpp
// filter_manager.cc:1077
void DownstreamFilterManager::prepareLocalReplyViaFilterChain(...) {
  createDownstreamFilterChain();
