```cpp
// header_map_impl.cc:410
size_t HeaderMapImpl::removeIf(const HeaderMap::HeaderMatchPredicate& predicate) {
  const size_t old_size = headers_.size();
  headers_.removeIf([&predicate, this](const HeaderEntryImpl& entry) {
    const bool to_remove = predicate(entry);
    if (to_remove) {
      auto lookup = staticLookup(entry.key().getStringView());
      if (lookup.has_value()) {
        if (lookup.value().entry_) {
          // Lines 417-424: clear the inline (O(1)) header table entry
          const uint32_t key_value_size =
              (*lookup.value().entry_)->key().size() + (*lookup.value().entry_)->value().size();
          subtractSize(key_value_size);
          *lookup.value().entry_ = nullptr;   // ← not covered
        }
      } else {
        subtractSize(entry.key().size() + entry.value().size());
      }
    }
    return to_remove;
  });
  return old_size - headers_.size();
}
```

### Why it is untested

`RemoveIf` in `header_map_impl_test.cc` (line 250) uses only custom non-inline
headers (`"X-postfix-foo"` etc.) that do not appear in the static lookup table.
The predicate therefore always falls into the `else` branch (line 425), leaving
the inline-header clear path at line 423 (`*lookup.value().entry_ = nullptr`)
completely uncovered. After this branch executes, the inline accessor (e.g.
`headers.ContentLength()`) should return `nullptr`, but this is never verified.

### Concrete test proposal

```
TEST(HeaderMapImplTest, RemoveIfClearsInlineHeader) {
  TestRequestHeaderMapImpl headers;
  // Add an inline (O(1)) header: content-length is a registered inline header.
  headers.setContentLength(42);
  ASSERT_NE(nullptr, headers.ContentLength());
  const uint64_t size_before = headers.byteSize();

  // Remove it via removeIf predicate.
  size_t removed = headers.removeIf([](const HeaderEntry& e) -> bool {
    return e.key().getStringView() == "content-length";
  });

  EXPECT_EQ(1UL, removed);
  EXPECT_EQ(nullptr, headers.ContentLength());   // inline slot cleared
  EXPECT_LT(headers.byteSize(), size_before);    // byte accounting updated
  headers.verifyByteSizeInternalForTest();

  // Also verify the header is gone from iteration.
  bool found = false;
  headers.iterate([&found](const HeaderEntry& e) -> HeaderMap::Iterate {
    if (e.key().getStringView() == "content-length") found = true;
    return HeaderMap::Iterate::Continue;
  });
  EXPECT_FALSE(found);
}
```

Add to `test/common/http/header_map_impl_test.cc`.

### Why it matters

After an `removeIf` that removes an inline header without clearing
`*lookup.value().entry_`, the `ContentLength()` accessor would return a
dangling pointer to freed memory. This is a use-after-free: any subsequent
code that calls `headers.ContentLength()` trusting it to be non-null would
read or write freed memory. The `verifyByteSizeInternalForTest()` call in the
proposed test would also catch any off-by-one in the `subtractSize` accounting.

